translate:
In the flow of worldly affairs, I seize the evening glow;
Gazing upward, I exclaim in bewilderment.
Who can support the heavens and the earth, holding them up?
The sea and the river are guided by the north wind.
The southern people dance in the fresh breeze, their homes newly built;
As the ashes fly westward, the three returns are left behind.
Only the solitary peak of Heavenly India remains;
Since it has arrived, it no longer needs to fly again.

Difficult matters can't be spoken, only sighs are heard;
A boiling sea, cooked in a pot, just like a ding.
Poverty and exhaustion add to our knowledge of destiny;
Old friends have stopped writing, it seems there's no need.
In official life, one sees the world like a giant ant;
A fish that can't leave its hometown for a thousand miles.
Already planning to return to agriculture and grow half a crop;
Still worried about the dragon year, when the Qin people rise.

Village surrounded by a ten-mile radius, Zhu Chen's land;
Through the seasons, we share our true camaraderie.
Our spirits are refreshed by the sweet wine and mountain streams,
As the fragrance of leeks cleanses our minds from worldly dust.
Recently in Yunnan, we find ourselves with little to do;
Who among the world knows this springtime like us?
In silent contemplation, we find no words can express our thoughts;
We do not compare ourselves to peach and plum blossoms.

Abandoning the gourd, the hermit father certainly speaks of rarity;
Resolving the seal, Tao Qian is not right or wrong.
The wind and rain seem to know of the changes in the world;
The rivers and mountains love their master and owner to return.
There are tea houses to soothe loneliness from time to time;
Heaven preserves the solitary awakening with a lotus robe.
I am also a cold winter plant under the pine tree;
We look at each other for miles to borrow the warmth of spring.

In the ninth month, the scenery's splendid once more;
Your home has no wine, and you sit with no wealth.
Although the green hills have failed to fulfill the chrysanthemum promise,
Contentment should be found in the sweetness of rice and wine.
The world is busy competing for drunken bliss;
Who can care about the solitary awakened sage?
Two associates exchange thoughts casually;
Together, they will attain an ordinary, plain sky.

Mangrove sandals, returning eastward, the sun is setting;
Old friends remain behind, who would lament their delay?
Several cups of wine to stagger drunkenness and hunger's cure;
A pillow for a deep sleep, finding comfort in one's home.
Lake and sea friends, many have passed away like grass;
Through the ages, the wind and flowers of the universe have remained.
Simply view events as if they were nothing;
Wandering through mountains and streams, poetry knows no bounds.

Two hills join waters, flowing between our lips; 
Three rooms of thatched cottage, with pines surrounding four neighbors. 
Flowers' shadows fall upon the pond, dusting the outer world; 
Birdsong welcomes guests, as spring tranquility ensues. 
Life has already been dedicated to the silkworms and the woods; 
Vivid phrases still follow, accompanied by fresh vegetables and wine. 
The taste of life is long-lasting, shared by brothers and friends; 
In the mountains beyond, who else knows what lies in store?

Inhale the businesslike air, its tone grim and clear;
Human leisure finds it hard to listen or describe.
Not divine, not ghostly, the pleasure of Dongting Lake;
For cranes and winds, the soldiers of the Feishu River.
Old leaves hum their high-pitched tune, while cold insects chirp in the bustling noise.
The annual events of the west wind's mechanical sound;
Entrusted to the heart of heaven, all will be made even.

Old and weary, I find no rest on my sweat-soaked pillow;
Rising to gaze at the celestial court, where silver rivers flow.
Fragmented mountains and remaining waters are desolate and bleak;
The bright moon and gentle breeze evoke a melancholy feeling deep.
There is no way to shut the door and block out the world outside;
It seems truly like an open-eyed dream in the South Pool.
Sitting here, I don't realize the east has already turned white;
Another life passes by, another night spent in vain.

In sunny weather, the roof tiles accompany each other well; 
How many people can appreciate its beauty and come to see it? 
Immediately, one can feel the wine's aroma filling the air; 
Together, we explore the world of books and brush away the dust. 
Viewing life as if there were no life; 
There's still time for us to return later in the day. 
We enjoy the fun moments, even when separated; 
The clouds and birds stop to rest, and they are at ease.

In harmony, we respond like bamboo and chime;
Rainy nights, we share a bed, only poetry in sight.
Through the broken channels, our boats return with enthusiasm;
We feel the passage of time, but only at the bath of orchids.
Our thoughts are difficult to share with the world's affairs;
With aging and illness, we move on to seek solace in monkhood.
Believe that all currents are destined to stay;
Otherwise, why would we have a heavenly father above?

In the world, all things are like wandering dust;
The shallow world is filled with noise and strife.
Who can tell the hands and feet of Lu and Wei?
The liver and gall of Yue and Qin abound.
Only you, my noble ancestor, were wise;
You treated your father as I treat mine.
I have followed in your footsteps, sharing your righteousness;
Our bond, like that of brothers, cannot be severed.
We depend on each other, like lips to teeth;
In leisure time, we share our illnesses and meals.
Your wisdom shines brightly, like ancient ways;
Difficult to express, but written on a silk cloth.
Now, I interact with your children, knowing their love exceeds all others;
Not saying that it's bland, but like relishing miles of water shield.
Their children and grandchildren are exceptional, worthy of admiration;
With thousands of books and notes at their disposal.
Success is just dirt, while scholarship requires depth;
Effort is focused, and action is self-reliant.
Expanding and promoting knowledge, supporting the boundaries of heaven and earth;
Books accumulate, not easily, yet unmistakably, as the heavens.
Not observing winter's closure, but spring's greenness emerging;
Knowing the roots of our ancestors, who cultivated our family tree.
All things in the wind, like cotton, are gone;
Only virtue remains, refined through practice.
Familiarity breeds no idle chatter;
Nostalgia and bitterness stir our feelings anew.
At seventy years old, I am out of touch with the times;
My eyes are dim, and I turn inward, ignoring the world's changes.
My ears are deaf to external sounds, avoiding noisy gatherings;
In my five-acre garden, I accept my poverty and solitude.
Vegetable gardens and wild paths, moonlit breezes at dawn;
With my children by my side, I take stock of life momentarily.
Extending my remaining time, fortunate to have kindness nearby;
No grand expectations, only to be a citizen of the world.
No more waiting for friends from afar, as I ride in a carriage, dreaming;
My true calling returns, as I embrace the people of the world.

Autumn arrives, the sky partly sunny and overcast; 
Sitting by the mountain window, I stretch my aching body. 
Trying to sleep, but worried about official duties; 
Fear of reciting poetry, for fear of stirring up hometown feelings. 
Letters from afar are hard to predict, clothes remain thin; 
Poor salary, accustomed to poverty, there's not much to spend. 
The fields of rice are ripe, rain is appropriate when falling, not excessive.
